.Dd March 30, 2026
.Dt VIS 1
.Os Kayoko
.Sh NAME
.Nm vis
.Nd display non-printable characters in a visual format
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Op Ar file ...
.Sh DESCRIPTION
The
.Nm
utility reads the given files (or standard input if no files are specified) 
and writes the content to standard output, converting non-printable 
characters into a visible representation.
.Pp
Characters are processed as follows:
.Bl -bullet -offset indent
.It
Printable ASCII characters are passed through unchanged.
.It
Common control characters are represented by standard C-style escape 
sequences (e.g.,
.Li \en
for newline,
.Li \er
for carriage return,
.Li \et
for tab).
.It
The backslash character
.Pq Li \e
is escaped as
.Li \e\e .
.It
All other non-printable characters are rendered as three-digit octal 
sequences preceded by a backslash 
.Pq e.g., Li \e001 .
.El
.Sh EXIT STATUS
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It 0
Success.
.It >0
An error occurred (e.g., a file could not be opened).
.El
.Sh EXAMPLES
To view the hidden characters in a binary file:
.Pp
.Dl $ vis /bin/ls
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Xr cat 1 ,
.Xr unvis 1
